## Bringr-93j.18 â€” committed window now rises and takes focus

**Root cause:** Three independent defects in the commit path, all masked by `FakeWindowSystem` (synchronous activation, no AX cache), which is why US-012 shipped "green" but broken.

**Fixes in `Bringr/WindowControl.swift`:**
1. **Activation race** â€” `restore()` gained a `reactivatingFrontmost: Bool = true` parameter; `commit` passes `false` so it no longer re-activates the prior frontmost app (whose async `NSRunningApplication.activate()` was racing â€” and often beating â€” the target's activation). Cancel paths keep the default.
2. **Stale AX cache** â€” `commit` now re-enumerates the target's app (`_ = system.windows(of: window.app)`) to refresh the element cache before un-minimize/raise/focus, so a stale handle can't make them silently no-op.
3. **macOS 14+ activation semantics** â€” `LiveWindowSystem.activate` also sets `kAXFrontmost` on the app element, so an accessory (`LSUIElement`) app reliably brings the app forward.

**Regression test (`BringrTests/WindowControlTests.swift`):** Instrumented the fake with `activationLog`/`enumerationLog`; the new test asserts a committed backgrounded-app window yields `activationLog == [target]` (race) and `enumerationLog.contains(target)` (cache-miss). I proved it has teeth â€” reverting `commit` to the old `restore()` makes it fail with `[prior, target]` and no enumerate.

**Quality gates:** `** BUILD SUCCEEDED **`, `swiftlint --strict` 0 violations (35 files), 167 tests / 0 failures. App builds, launches, runs clean (PID confirmed). AC4's on-screen confirmation needs Accessibility permission + a physical trigger, so the live focus is best eyeballed by a human â€” documented in `progress.md` alongside a new reusable codebase pattern.

